rComments: Readings help w/theory. Class is equal understanding and memorization. Doesn't give enough practice problems, but exams are always things we've seen in class, sometimes only 1 slide. Material is easy, but the questions are written in a hard way. Don't overthink. Final exam was easier than midterms. Better midterm replaces worse midterm. GOTOCLASS!!
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: he teaches the hardest course of this program so i guess he gets a bad rep because of it but he's not that bad prof. he goes way too fast though especially when drawing complex mechanisms. i'm generally lost at all times during his lectures. his exams are okay its just the subject is really tough and he doesnt help make it a lot easier

Excellent prof with very balanced course, presents the material very well and is able to simplify the concepts during office hours. The course covers plenty of content but it is manageable if you keep on top of the practice questions.

Thought I'd be doing cool science, but my project was pretty uninspiring. He complained to all of the honours students that we were not working hard enough and provided little to no guidance. He treats majority of his lab pretty badly from what I saw. Steer clear, there are better labs to join.

I failed the first midterm and so did most of the class. Thankfully he allowed for it to be discarded. Cycloadditions require the most problem-solving as it is tricky to know which part of the molecule will do what. But the rest of the course is based on memorization. Tests are actually fair and easier than the problem sets. Few office hours :/
Good professor, genuinely enjoys what he teaches but one of the harder courses you'll take at the university. Must be ready to go beyond textbook and assignments to receive an A.

Best lecturer I've had in 3 years of the program. Super knowledgable guy; he's extremely high in his field. You learn a lot of material. Class is hard: the first midterm will wreck you. After that, it's more straightforward. Bell curves usually end up being necessary and he'll change the midterm weighting. Study your ass off and you'll be fine.

Excellent lecturer and you can tell this guy's a genius... that being said this is without a doubt the hardest class I have ever taken at university to such an extent where you actually wonder why it has to be this hard... don't take this class if you don;t have to for the sake of your CGPA.

This course is NOT for you if you dislike organic chemistry and made it by the past organic chemistry courses. You can put in a lot of work and still get an F if you fail to truly understand and learn to link the course material to complex problem solving.  For those repeating this course (which is a lot), just dont! Save your soul and happiness.

Pratt was a very good prof! The material itself is difficult to grasp but he doesn't throw really hard or curveball questions at you on tests. As long as you understand and can pick out what the question is about it is straightforward. He was very accessible and was more than happy to set up appointments to go over your questions.
He is good at teaching in his lectures but his tests are brutal! The only way to succeed is if you practice practice problems everyday for two hours. It is brutal!

Hard course with more memorizing then you would think.  Questions are mostly fair, they are present in the notes, but that means you have to memorize next to all of them. Gives problem sets and old exams that help you prepare. Really there for the students, made adjustments to marking scheme to boast the class's marks.

Great lecturer, really nice prof and the content reflected the material in class. BUT that marking for the midterms in finals (worth a high percentage of your grade) is super super tough. Would study for weeks and still get a terrible grade because the one specific thing he wanted you to say wasn't there. This class will break your heart!
His midterms and final are challenging so I recommend that you practice the additional problems plus the textbook problems. Also attend lectures and the DGDs and you're good.

Great lecturer. Recommended Textbook is actually amazing, and not garbage at all like first year classes. Provides alot of practice problems with answers, even more if you do the textbook questions (it has a good solution manual). Need to practice and attend class to do well. Midterms were easy, final exam was brutal, but I think it was curved so:)

Here's a good lecturer and he's really clear with the notes. However, his exams are impossible. A+ students will fail the final, and he doesn't even care. I'm a chemistry major, and this is the only class I've ever failed! Avoid him if you can, otherwise GET A TUTOR. The material is VERY easy, the exams will murder you though.

Dr. Pratt is a great lecturer, I actually enjoyed attending his lectures. BUT his tests are SO HARD, and he is an insane marker. The midtermexam is 10 times harder than the material learned during lectures. Also, there are no online resources and practice problems. It's impossible to do well in a chemist class when there is no practice problems.

I went into orgo 3 hating chemistry and left absolutely loving it!  The prof was amazing, very approchable (though it didn't seem so  at first) and helpful when you went to see him during office hours.  The exams reflected very closely the material learned in class and he provides lots of practice questions to get you ready for them.

Great Professor, and AMAZING lecturer.  Material is difficult (probably because material is hard), but he teaches it well. NEED TO PRACTICE MANY EXAMPLES TO DO WELL. He's always willing to help with problems during office hours.

Take everything you know about how to study Organic chemistry and throw it out the window. Start fresh, its the only way you can pass this maze and cluster of material he dares call Organic chemistry. Tests are crazy hard and questions come out of nowhere. Also, memorization will be your friend.
Ridiculously hard, for no reason. Will ask crazy complicated derivatives of things presented in class, making application of knowledge extremely difficult.
